---
import Layout from '@layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '@components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '@components/Footer.astro';
---

<Layout
	title='How to use box shadows with Tailwind CSS'
	description='Learn how to use box shadows in Tailwind CSS, including custom and arbitrary values for modern UI design.'
	ogType='article'
	keywords={['tailwind css', 'box shadows', 'css shadows', 'tailwind tutorial']}
	article={{
		publishedTime: '2024-09-12T00:00:00Z',
		author: 'Vivian',
		tags: ['tailwind', 'css', 'shadows'],
	}}>
	<Header />

	<div class="container flex flex-col pt-36 lg:pt-44 xl:pt-52 mb-20 lg:flex-row">
		<div class="mx-auto w-full max-w-3xl">
			<h2
				class="font-Recoleta font-normal text-black xl:text-[43px]/[48px]! lg:text-4xl! text-3xl!"
			>
			How to use box shadows with Tailwind CSS, including custom and arbitrary values
			</h2>
			<div
				class="border-grey-light flex flex-col border-b pb-5 md:flex-row md:items-center"
			>
				<div class="flex pt-4">
					<p class="text-black font-body text-sm md:text-base">
						By
						<span class="font-bold">Vivian</span>
					</p>
					<span class="text-black px-2 text-sm md:text-base">/</span>
					<p class="text-black font-body text-sm md:text-base">
						September 12, 2024
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div
				class="prose-blog prose relative mt-8 max-w-none md:prose-lg prose-headings:mt-4 prose-li:marker:text-black text-black font-Gordita"
			>
				<h3>Intro</h3>
				<p>Since they were introduced in 2009, shadows have been a great way to add some flair to any design. Shadows have evolved over the years and now they are incredibly flexible, even allowing for multiple shadows on a single element, similar to how the background-image property works.</p>
				<h4>Prerequisites</h4>
				<p>Since they were introduced in 2009, shadows have been a great way to add some flair to any design. Shadows have evolved over the years and now they are incredibly flexible, even allowing for multiple shadows on a single element, similar to how the background-image property works.</p>
				<p>As a quick recap, you apply shadows using the box-shadow CSS property and the property allows up to 5 values per shadow: x offset, y offset, blur-radius, spread-radius, and color. If you want to add multiple shadows just separate them with a comma.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="mt-8 flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center">
				<span
					class="text-black mr-4 font-medium text-lg md:text-base"
					>Share this article on:</span
				>
				<div class="flex gap-2.5 mt-2 items-center">
					<button id="twitter">
						<img src="images/lazy.svg" data-src="images/icon/icon-twitter.svg" alt="" class="lazy-img h-9">
					</button>
					<button id="linkedin">
						<img src="images/lazy.svg" data-src="images/icon/icon-linkedin.svg" alt="" class="lazy-img h-9">
					</button>
					<button id="reddit">
						<img src="images/lazy.svg" data-src="images/icon/icon-reddit.svg" alt="" class="lazy-img h-9">
					</button>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	<Footer />
</Layout>
